Running a Monolith on the HashiStack

This guide explains how the generated monolith.nomad job specification manages a monolithic application using Nomad, Consul, and Vault.

How the Core Architecture Works

                        ┌──────────────────┐
                        │  Nomad Server    │
                        │ (The Orchestrator)
                        └────────┬─────────┘
                                 │ Schedules Job
                                 ▼
                     ┌──────────────────────┐
                     │     Server Node      │
                     │                      │
 ┌──────────┐        │  ┌────────────────┐  │        ┌──────────┐
 │  Consul  │◄───────┼──┤ Monolith Task  ├──┼───────►│  Vault   │
 │ (Routing)│ Registers│└────────────────┘  │Fetches │(Secrets) │
 └──────────┘        │                      │Secrets └──────────┘
                     └──────────────────────┘


1. Nomad (The Brains)

Instead of manually copying code to a server and running it, you submit the monolith.nomad file to your Nomad cluster.

Scheduling: Nomad looks at the resources block (demanding 2 CPUs and 4GB RAM) and scans your servers to find one that has these resources available.

Self-Healing: If the physical server running your monolith dies, Nomad automatically schedules a brand-new instance of your monolith on another server in the cluster.

2. Vault (The Guard)

A common problem with monoliths is storing database credentials, API keys, and SSL certificates safely.

Direct Retrieval: The vault and template blocks in the jobspec configure Nomad to authenticate with Vault.

No hardcoded secrets: Nomad fetches the database username and password at the exact millisecond the application starts, writing them directly into the environment variables.

Auto-Rotation: If security teams update the database password in Vault, Nomad automatically restarts the monolith (configured by change_mode = "restart") with the new password, ensuring zero-downtime secret rotations.

3. Consul (The Switchboard)

Because Nomad places your monolith on whichever server has the CPU/RAM room, the IP address and port of your application might change dynamically.

Service Discovery: The service block registers the application with Consul under the name "monolith-service".

Zero-Configuration Routing: Your load balancer (like Nginx, HAProxy, or Traefik) query Consul's DNS (e.g., monolith-service.service.consul) to find exactly where the monolith is currently running.

Health Checks: Consul continuously pings /healthz. If your monolith locks up or runs out of database connections, Consul stops sending user traffic to it immediately while Nomad works on restarting it.

Running this Job

To run this configuration on your Nomad cluster, use the Nomad Command Line Interface (CLI):

# 1. Format and validate the file to ensure no syntax errors
nomad job validate monolith.nomad

# 2. Plan the deployment to see what changes Nomad will make
nomad job plan monolith.nomad

# 3. Run/Deploy the job
nomad job run monolith.nomad
